The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Thursday, August 19, 2004 				 Alert on fake notes 
 OUR BUREAU 																								Barasat/Burdwan, Aug. 18: Police have issued an alert to all border police stations, particularly in south Bengal, to keep an eye on the local cattle markets as investigation showed a large number of fake currency notes was ploughed into the system there. 																								Inter-district gangs were procuring the notes from Bangladesh and circulating them in the cattle fairs, mainly in Nadia, Hooghly, Burdwan and North 24-Parganas. 																								Officials reached the conclusion after several arrests blew the lid off fake notes rackets. One Afarul Islam was held from Selimabad in Burdwan district and he revealed that he was getting the notes from Taherpur in North 24-Parganas. 																								Earlier this month, two more persons were arrested from Bongaon in North 24-Parganas and 27 fake Rs 100 notes were recovered from them. They revealed another gang was operating from Karimpur in Nadia. It was bringing in fake Rs 500 notes from Bangladesh across the Gede border.																								The problem is typical of the border areas of Bongaon and Basirhat. The BSF has to stop supply of these notes from Bangladesh. We are tackling the problem within our jurisdiction. We are sure about one thing  no fake note is being printed in North 24-Parganas, said Praveen Kumar, the district superintendent of police. 
